<br>
<i>and extra mana waste.</i><br>
<br>
What?<br>
<br>
dazzle = 1.30 mana per second of mez<br>
entrance = 1.18 mana per second of mez<br>
enthrall = 1.04 mana per second of mez<br>
<br>
<i>The recast time on dazzle is a non issue for most enchanters, since you will normally Flux ( or shift ) on a mezz resist anyway.</i><br>
<br>
depends on the situation more and more these days. I can channel through a mez on a unhasted mob actively beating on me more times than not. it is more efficent in many situations just to channel through the mez rather than dicking around with stuns or resisted stuns and attracting the attention of adds that may be beating on the tanks instead.<br>
<br>
if entrance or enthrall bounces, I don't *have* to stun to give dazzle time to refresh.<br>
<br>
<i>The only reason i use dazzle all the time at present is , frankly because im lazy.</i> <br>
<br>
Ah yes, that makes dazzle better.<br>
<br>
<i>I would respectfully disagree with the fact that entrance / enthrall is always the best spell , however. Dazzle allows the control of larger trains as well /shrug.</i><br>
<br>
entrance's cast is 2.5, refresh is 3.75, spell recovery is 2. This means it takes 8.75 seconds to mez a mob and be ready for the next one. In the space of 72 seconds ( the length of entrance )... you can mez 8 mobs and have about 3 seconds left over, assuming an ideal situation where you target instantly and have no resists.<br>
<br>
dazzle's cast is 2.5, refresh is 5, spell recovery is 2. It takes 9.5 seconds to mez a mob with dazzle and be ready for the next one. In the space of 96 seconds ( the length of dazzle ).. you can mez 10 mobs and have less than a second left over. Again, this assumes an ideal situation with no resists and you target instantly.<br>
<br>
Given real world situations, you could perhaps mez one more mob consistently with dazzle than you could with entrance.<br>
<br>
<i>Dazzle ( all spells actually ) are a bitch to channel when you first get them...</i><br>
<br>
Respecfully disagree with this statement. Chance to channel a spell is a function of your /loc when you started casting the spell, your /loc when you complete the spell[1], and your channelling score. I channel through Forlorn Deeds at about the same rate as Shiftless Deeds when a mob is actively beating on me.... which is to say, not often, but it happens.<br>
<br>
[1] try this out.... take a long casting spell like shield of magi or pet or such. back yourself into a corner so that you have a nice way to get back to your original loc. start casting the spell. Run around the room. Return to your original spot about 2 seconds before the spell completes. I've done it before where I haven't even gotten the "you regain concentration" message.<br>
